<div id="review_1722354669" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1722354669" />
    <a title="Mariana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24318470-mariana"><img alt="Mariana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1584527485p2/24318470.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1722354669?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mariana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mariana" href="/user/show/24318470-mariana">Mariana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781509826698" href="/book/show/28260522-tales-of-mystery-imagination">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24318470-mariana?shelf=read-in-2022">read-in-2022</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1722354669&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1722354669" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1405424354502287337"><br/>“They could picture to their imaginations a mode – many modes – and a motive – many motives; and because it was not impossible that either of these numerous modes and motives could have been the actual one, they have taken it for granted that one of them must. But the ease with which these variable fancies were entertained, and the very plausibility which each assumed, should have been understood as indicative rather of the difficulties than of the facilities which must attend elucidation. I hav</span>
  <span id="freeText1405424354502287337" style="display:none"><br />“They could picture to their imaginations a mode – many modes – and a motive – many motives; and because it was not impossible that either of these numerous modes and motives could have been the actual one, they have taken it for granted that one of them must. But the ease with which these variable fancies were entertained, and the very plausibility which each assumed, should have been understood as indicative rather of the difficulties than of the facilities which must attend elucidation. I have before observed that it is by prominences above the plane of the ordinary, that reason feels her way, if at all, in her search for the true, and that the proper question in cases such as this, is not so much ‘what has occurred?’ as ‘what has occurred that has never occurred before?’…”<br /><br />I must admit it took me a while to read this book. Luckily, this is a collection of independent stories that the only thing they have in common is the strangeness of the events described in them; so, I took my time reading them. I’m not particularly fan of mysteries but I became very fond of Edgar Allan Poe’s descriptions of mysterious events; the stories are, in fact, extraordinary but what I really liked about them was the way he wrote them. Every word is explicitly there for a reason, nothing is out of meaning and the fact that he usually puts himself in the stories gives an extra chilling perspective of the tale. <br /><br />The stories that had the biggest impact on me were ‘The Mystery of Marie Rogêt’, ‘The Fall of the House of Usher’, ‘The Pit and the Pendulum’, ‘The Oblong Box’, ‘Ligeia’ and ‘Loss of Breath’. These were my favourites because, by he’s way of writing, Poe made me shiver a little bit whilst reading each one of these. Nevertheless, he was a genius because every story shows him, rationalizing towards possible explanations for these almost impossible situations, that may or may not have occurred, never reaching a direct conclusion, thus maintaining the suspense about these paranormal events, so the reader keeps thinking about them after ending the stories. And that is why these passed the test of time and are now part of classic novel, that is very much worth reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1405424354502287337" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

